On Thu, Oct 23, 2008 at 2:25 PM, Raphael Parree &lt;rparree@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; David,
&gt;
&gt; Just to make sure: do you mean that the AllMembersSupplier&#39;s addFields
&gt; method should filter fields those having a @DataPoint annotation and not
&gt; just all that are public and static?
&gt;
&gt; Raphael
&gt;
&gt; On Thu, Oct 23, 2008 at 7:46 PM, David Saff &lt;david@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt;&gt; Raphael,
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; You&#39;re right. It&#39;s a bug. Only @DataPoint fields should be used.
&gt;&gt; Can you log the bug? Thanks,
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; David Saff
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; On Thu, Oct 23, 2008 at 3:47 AM, Raphael Parree
&gt;&gt; &lt;rparree@...&lt;rparree%40gmail.com&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; wrote:
&gt;&gt; &gt; Hi,
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; Looking at the default data supplier for Theories (
&gt;&gt; &gt; org.junit.experimental.theories.internal.AllMembersSupplier) it seems to
&gt;&gt; me
&gt;&gt; &gt; the @DataPoint annotation only has an effect on methods. If that is
&gt;&gt; indeed
&gt;&gt; &gt; the case perhaps the annotation should be defined with Target
&gt;&gt; &gt; ElementType.METHOD?
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; The reason is that the AllMembersSupplier&#39;s getValueSources uses the
&gt;&gt; &gt; addFields which includes all public static fields regardless of any
&gt;&gt; &gt; annotation (except for the plurar version DataPoints for arrays).
&gt;&gt; Therefore
&gt;&gt; &gt; it does not matter whether you use the @DataPoint annotation on fields.
&gt;&gt; &gt; Perhaps the implementation of addFields should use it, in which case the
&gt;&gt; &gt; target of the @DataPoint annotation should include fields.
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; Thanks,
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; Raphael
